<p><i><b>Of Mice and Men</b></i> is a <a href="/wiki/Novella" title="Novella">novella</a> written by <a href="/wiki/Nobel_Prize_in_Literature" title="Nobel Prize in Literature">Nobel Prize</a>-winning author <a href="/wiki/John_Steinbeck" title="John Steinbeck">John Steinbeck</a>. Published in <a href="/wiki/1937_in_literature" title="1937 in literature">1937</a>, it tells the tragic story of George Milton and Lennie Small, two displaced <a href="/wiki/Migrant_worker" title="Migrant worker">migrant</a> <a href="/wiki/Ranch" title="Ranch">ranch</a> workers during the <a href="/wiki/Great_Depression" title="Great Depression">Great Depression</a> in <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</a>.</p>
<p>Based on Steinbeck's own experiences as a <a href="/wiki/Hobo" title="Hobo">bindle stiff</a> in the <a href="/wiki/1920" title="1920">1920s</a> (before the arrival of the <a href="/wiki/Okie" title="Okie">Okies</a> he would vividly describe in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Grapes_of_Wrath" title="The Grapes of Wrath">The Grapes of Wrath</a></i>), the title is taken from <a href="/wiki/Robert_Burns" title="Robert Burns">Robert Burns</a>'s poem, <i><a href="/wiki/To_a_Mouse" title="To a Mouse">To a Mouse</a></i>, which are often quoted as: "The best-laid plans of mice and men/often go awry," though in the original <a href="/wiki/Scots_language" title="Scots language">Scots</a> of the poem they read: "The best laid schemes o' mice an' men/Gang aft agley."</p>
<p>Required reading in many high schools, <i>Of Mice and Men</i> has been a frequent target of <a href="/wiki/Censorship" title="Censorship">censors</a> for what some consider offensive and vulgar language; consequently, it appears on the <a href="/wiki/American_Library_Association" title="American Library Association">American Library Association</a>'s list of the <i>Most Challenged Books of 21st Century</i>.</p>
